          <h2>Short Answer</h2>
          <p>Classical musicians rely on music theory to understand notation, interpret composers’ intentions, and perform with stylistic accuracy across various instruments — from strings and winds to percussion and keyboard.</p>

          <h2>Why It Matters in Classical Music</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Sheet Music Interpretation:</strong> Theory helps you read complex rhythms, dynamics, articulations, and phrasing markings with confidence.</li>
            <li><strong>Ensemble Synchronization:</strong> Knowing harmonic structure and form improves coordination in orchestras and chamber groups.</li>
            <li><strong>Stylistic Awareness:</strong> Understanding periods (Baroque, Classical, Romantic, Modern) guides proper performance technique.</li>
            <li><strong>Instrument Versatility:</strong> Whether violin, flute, cello, trumpet, or piano — theory informs fingerings, bowings, breath control, and harmonic placement.</li>
            <li><strong>Score Analysis:</strong> Musicians can interpret motifs, counterpoint, cadences, and orchestration choices.</li>
          </ul>

          <h2>Common Misconceptions</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Theory is too rigid:</strong> In truth, composers used theory creatively — it gives structure, not restrictions.</li>
            <li><strong>Only composers need theory:</strong> Performers use theory every time they read a score or play in an ensemble.</li>
            <li><strong>Classical musicians only follow rules:</strong> Interpretation requires informed creativity, shaped by theoretical understanding.</li>
          </ul>

          <h2>Practical Classical Exercises</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Score Marking:</strong> Analyze cadences, themes, and modulations on your sheet music.</li>
            <li><strong>Interval Training:</strong> Develop pitch accuracy for orchestral tuning and sight‑singing.</li>
            <li><strong>Orchestral Listening:</strong> Follow a full score while listening — identify instrument entries.</li>
            <li><strong>Counterpoint Practice:</strong> Try writing simple two‑part counterpoint to understand melodic independence.</li>
          </ul>

          <h2>Quick Reference</h2>
          <pre class="code">Classical Cadence Types:
- Perfect Authentic Cadence (V – I)
- Imperfect Authentic Cadence
- Plagal Cadence (IV – I)
- Half Cadence (ending on V)
- Deceptive Cadence (V – vi)
          </pre>

          <div class="callout">
            <strong>Tip:</strong> Focus on reading, intervals, and harmonic function — these unlock expressive classical performance.
          </div>

          <h2>Putting It Together</h2>
          <p>Theory connects musicians across centuries. From Bach's counterpoint to Beethoven's motifs, it gives classical performers depth, precision, and interpretive power.</p>

